  "question": "A new program had 60 downloads in the first month. The number of downloads in the second month was three times as many as the downloads in the first month, but then reduced by 30% in the third month. How many downloads did the program have total over the three months?",
  "prompt": "A new program had 60 downloads in the first month. The number of downloads in the second month was three times as many as the downloads in the first month, but then reduced by 30% in the third month. How many downloads did the program have total over the three months?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "366",
  "generated_text": "To find the total number of downloads over the three months, we calculate the downloads for each month individually.\n\n1.  **First Month**:\n    The problem states there were 60 downloads.\n    $$ \\text{Downloads}_1 = 60 $$\n\n2.  **Second Month**:\n    The number of downloads in the second month was three times as many as the first month.\n    $$ \\text{Downloads}_2 = 3 \\times 60 = 180 $$\n\n3.  **Third Month**:\n    The number of downloads in the third month was reduced by 30% from the second month's amount.\n    First, calculate 30% of the second month's downloads:\n    $$ 30\\% \\text{ of } 180 = 0.30 \\times 180 = 54 $$\n    Then, subtract this reduction from the second month's total:\n    $$ \\text{Downloads}_3 = 180 - 54 = 126 $$\n    (Alternatively, you can calculate the remaining percentage: $100\\% - 30\\% = 70\\%$, so $0.70 \\times 180 = 126$).\n\n4.  **Total Downloads**:\n    Add the downloads from all three months together:\n    $$ \\text{Total} = \\text{Downloads}_1 + \\text{Downloads}_2 + \\text{Downloads}_3 $$\n    $$ \\text{Total} = 60 + 180 + 126 $$\n    $$ \\text{Total} = 360 + 126 = 486 $$\n\nThe total number of downloads over the three months is 486.\n\n\\boxed{486}\n",
